        <h2 class="content-h2">Frequently Asked <em>Questions</em></h2>
        <div class="faq-list" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">How many injections will I need?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Most patients receive a course of 1 to 3 injections spaced one week apart, depending on the type of HA product used and the severity of the condition. Single-injection formulations are also available. Dr. Sarish Sharma will recommend the optimal course after your clinical assessment.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Is it painful?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">The injection involves a brief sharp sensation similar to a blood test. Some patients feel mild pressure inside the joint during injection. A local anaesthetic is applied beforehand if needed. Mild soreness for 24–48 hours after the injection is normal and expected. Most patients describe it as significantly less uncomfortable than anticipated.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">How long does the relief last?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Clinical studies show relief lasting between 6 and 12 months on average. Individual results vary based on the severity of arthritis, body weight, activity level, and the specific HA product used. The treatment can be repeated when relief diminishes — most patients do well with a course every 6–12 months.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Can this be done for the hip as well as the knee?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Yes. Viscosupplementation is effective for both knee and hip arthritis. Hip injections are performed under ultrasound guidance to ensure accurate placement into the hip joint space. The procedure and recovery are essentially the same as for the knee.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Is this safe for diabetic patients?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Hyaluronic acid injections are generally safe for diabetic patients and do not cause the blood sugar spikes associated with corticosteroid injections. This makes viscosupplementation a preferred option for diabetic patients with arthritis. Dr. Sarish Sharma will review your complete medical history before the procedure.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

